{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_queenofspades_ver01/data/sn83045462/00280608750/1958042201/0587.xml":{"full_text":"12-Year Low Hit by Pay\nSpent on Hard Goods\nl> tbt AwacteUd Pr*u\nThe percentage of take-home pay which American* epend\non durable good* such aa autos and appliances la at a 12-year\nlow.\nIn a review of spending habit*, the Commerce Department\nsaid yesterday the only comparable dip since mld-1948 was dur\ning the 1852 steel strike.\nDuring the 1946-68 period, there was an Increase in the\npercentage of take-home pay\nspent on nondurable*\u2014food,\ngasoline, etc ano services,\nhousing and utility charges.\nAll In all. the department\nsaid, consumer buying during\nthe current recession has de\nclined about In line with the\ntotal reduction In consumer\nIncome.\nFrloes Have Increased\nHowever, since prices have\nIncreased, the spending drop\nof about 1 per cent actually\nwas a bit more pronounced\nin terms of the volume of goods\nand services bought.\nPrice Increases, the report\nsaid, were more prevalent for\nsuch Items as food, housing,\nand utility charges which have\nbeen affected only slightly by\nthe business slump. Gasoline\nsales also have held up well\nThe Items which have been\nhit hardest are automobiles,\nappliances, home furnishings\nand all clothing except shoes.\nIn Its monthly survey of\ncurrent business, the depart\nment said changes in spending\nTwo Labor Chiefs Link\nAutomation to Slump\nSr th\u00ab Aunctatrd Prf\u00abl\nTwo labor union officials con\ntended today that automated\nfactories have not produced\nthe expanded employment and\nlower prices they said experts\nhad promised.\nAlbert Whitehouse. director\nof the AFL-CIO Industrial\nUnion Department, and Elmer\nJ. Maloy. industrial engineering\nchief of the Steelworkers Union,\nsaid automation so far has\nproved to be the bane rather\nthan the boon of the American\nworker.\nBoth blamed the recession at\nleast in part on new automatic\nmachines, many of them guided\nelectronically, that have pro\nvided increased industrial ca\npacity with fewer workers.\nConference on Problems\nBoth advanced these views in\ntalks prepared for a day-long\nconference on automation prob\nlems called by the AFL-ClO's\nIUD for some 200 union mem\nber*.\n\"It's time to point out that\nautomation an dother major\ntechnological change have failed\nto bring automatically those\nthings promised so blithely.\"\nMr. Whitehouse said, adding:\n\"Where are the great num\nbers of more highly skilled jobs?\nWhere are the lower prices?\nWhere are the jobs for every\nbody that were virtually guar\nanteed to us?\n\u201cSome of us have been kid\nding ourselves about the pur\nenterprise system, and prob\npose of technology undei our\nably under any other system.\nThe purpose of better machin-\nReligious News Writers\nElect Cleveland Man\nThe Religious New* Writer*\u2019\nAssociation yesteday elected\nRichard Wager of the Cleve\nland Plain Dealer as president.\nHe succeeds Caspar Nannes,\nreligious news editor of The\nStar.\nThe group last night pre\nsented the James O. Supple\nMemorial Award to Roy Cov\nington of the Charlotte <N. C.)\nObserver. The award, made\nannually for outstanding re\nporting of religious news, is\nnamed in honor of the late\nchurch editor of the Chicago\nSun-Times. It consists of a\ncitation and SIOO cash.\nRoscoe Drummond. New York\nHerald Tribune columnist was\nthe speaker at the award din\nner.\nfftSTYKAKE\nSo many kinds! So good\u2014so fresh-any time!\nf your daily energy treat\nk\\-\ndelicious DESSERT\nKRIMPETS\ngreat for COFFEE BREAK d\nCREAMIES\nchocolate or vanilla\ntempting at TV TIME\nk,* rs chocolate, butter cream,\ncocoanut\nguaranteed always fresh\ncakes and pies\n4 Mr. Dtaltri For itrviet call LUdlow 2-OM7\n\nhabits are slow to develop but;\nadded:\n\"The postponabillty of many\ndurable purchases la reflected\nin lower buying during period* i\nof recession, and a \u2018catching 1\nup' in ensuing recovery pe\nriods.\"\nLow of Ills Per Cent\nIt said the percentage of take\nhome pay spent for durable\ngoods hit a 12-year low of 101?\nper cent In the first three\nmonths of 1057. The report\nsaid about 80 per cent of the\ndecline was attributable to\n1 fewer auto sales.\nThe percentage spent for\nnondurables Increased in the;\nsame period from 48 1 a per cent\nto 47 per cent and the ratio of\nspending for services also\ni inched upward.\nAs reported earlier. Ameri\ncans for the first time since\nmid -1954 paid off their debts\nfaster than they contracted\nnew. ones In early 1958. Tae|\nI slump In auto buying was pri\nmarily responsible.\nrry is to cut labor costs by elim\n.[mating jobs.\"\nAnswer Always Same\nMr. Maloy said the steel In\n-1 dustry has doubled capacity in\ns a few years using fewer produc\ntion workers. He said the auto\nindustry has enough capacity\nfor triple the country's demand\nand requires fewer employes.\n\"The answer is always the\nsame.\" Maloy said, \"more and\nj more production, with less and\nless employes, yet higher and\nhigher selling prices for the\nproducts.\nt \"Either the increased produc\ntlon by improved methods costs\nj more than the old hand-made\nproduct or the corporations are\nextorting more from the public\nthan their products are worth.\"\nMr. Whitehouse said Presi\ndent Elsenhower now is urging\ni the public to buy more, but\nhe said factory workers are\nearning less this year than in\n5 1957 and are unable to spend\nmore unless they earn more.\nt Insurance Rise\ni Asked in State\nRICHMOND. April 22 (JPV\u2014\nThe State Corporation Com\nmission will hold a hearing\nThursday on a request by the\n1 Virginia Insurance Rating Bu\nreau for higher rates on col\nlision insttHmce for private\nautomobile*\nThe revised rate schedule\nsubmitted by the bureau ask*\nfor a rise of 8 per cent in\nrates and a 30.4 per cent tn\ncrease in rates for cars owned\nby unmarried men under 25\nyears of age.\nOther new officers elected\nyesterday are Richard Phil\nbrick of the Chicago Tribune.\nAdon Taft of the Miami Herald, j\nWillmer Thorkelson of the\nMinneapolis Star and William\nRose of the Oakland Tribune,!\nvice presidents: Dolores McCa\nhlll of the Chicago Sun-Times,\ntreasurer, and Erik Modean of\nthe Lutheran News Service, sec\nretary.\nAt the memorial service in\nWashington Cathedral, the as\nsociation paid tribute to the\nlate William Dlnwoodie. long\ntime church editor of the Cleve\nland News.\nMrs. Betha Prppeard. 86-\nycar-old church editor of the\nBoston Globe, was honored by\nthe association for her 50 years\nin religious journalism.\nAulomat Planl\nViolence Told\nOfficials of the Horn d i Har\ndsrt Baking Co. of Phtl\u00abd\u00bblnhia\ntestified today 120 or 125 ma\njor acts of violence including\nbeating* of employes marked\na 1955-58 union organising\ndrive against the automat firm.\nThe testimony before the\nSenate Rackets Investigating\nCommittee came from Leonard\nW. Lowther. president of the\nfirm; Daniel J. Hanlon, tr.. It*\nj chief counsel and assistant to\n[the president, and Bernard M.\nBortsh. counsel.\nThe three, taking the wit\nness stand together, named\nPhiladelphia locals of four\nunions as participating in the\norganising drive, but said they\nwere In no position to say who\nwas responsible for the beat\nings. damage to trucks and\nother violence.\nThey named local* 107 of the\nTeamslrrs Union: 195 of the\nButchers and Meat Cutters\nUnion, 137 of the Restaurant\nEmployes Union and No. 8 of\nthe Baker and Confectionery\nWorkers Union as participating\nin the campaign. They said that\nwhat took place was not a\nstrike but an unsuccessful at\ntempt to recruit the company's\nworkers into those four unions.\nRobert P. Kennedy, the com\nmittee's counsel, said the hear\ning would deal also with an al\nleged shakedown effort against\nI the company in the midst of\nthe violence.\nor V-- V m\n\nj Missing power on hills?\nMissing \u201cgo\u201d on getaway?\n\u2014T-\nj Missing money with low mileage?\n\ni!\nChances are you 